content.description:
Climb up the crack in the corner to the left of Feast and Famine.   

  Karabin's book says to to eventually traverse left and up gulley to rappel off Neptune's anchors, but just as well you can traverse slightly right and rappel off of Feast and Famine's anchors.
content.protection: Small to large gear, can be climbed with a full set of nuts and hexes.  Bolted anchors.
content.location: To the left of Feast and Famine.

content.description:
Scramble up to a ledge and optionally clip the first bolt of "Impending Doom".  Follow the crack and either step left to hit the anchors of "Impending Doom" or venture further on easier ground.  A small tree makes for a natural anchor should the route be followed to completion. 

  This route lists as a 5.3 in the pocket guide but I would grade it a 5.6.  Also be aware that the rappel off the tree may require two ropes -- it would certainly be close.  I rapped off the tree to the anchors of "Impending Doom".
content.protection: Large to small pro.  Optional bolt and anchors.
content.location: Dihedral between "Impending Doom" and "Schizophrenic Blvd" on the creek right.  Route #26 in Marty Karabin's "Road Area" (September 2008) pocket guide.

content.description: One of the better crack climbs at Atlantis and will hopefully clean up more. This route is listed as two pitches (5.10c) in Marty’s guide although that doesn’t make a lot of sense to me. If I were to climb to the top I’d do it all in one pitch. The traditional pitch two is short and really easy.The route starts with some slippery slab moves into the sweet hand crack above. Above that lies a short flakey off-width that felt like the crux to me although this is no 5.10c off-width. Above is a broken roof with big holds. After you pull the roof either build a gear belay or continue up a couple of easy moves and traverse right and use the bolted anchor on top of Public Hanging.
content.protection: Double cams from BD .3-3, single nuts and 4, optional extra 2-4, optional 5.
content.location: On the north and left side of the main Atlantis Canyon. Look for the vertical hand crack that widens then has a broken small roof at its top.

climbs.name: Unknown crack to right of Armed and Dangerous.

content.description: Blocky, wide crack with lots of great feet and stemming. Pro is a bit trixy in spots but adequate. Overall enjoyable and a nice warm up. I used anchor for armed and dangerous but it should be extended and also an extended directional placed in crack if toproping.
content.protection: Doubles through #4, nuts, a few alpine draws.
content.location: Between the unknown 5.9 crack and armed and dangerous. Access either by direct bulge start out of cave (5.10) or ramp to its right, as for the 5.9 crack, but then continue left from ramp up incipient crack toward wide, blocky crack.

content.description: Climb the obvious roof to the left of the waterfall/dam thing. It goes up big positive holds to a crack. Pulling the roof is the hardest part, but once you get the big pocket it's over.
content.protection: 7 bolts, shuts. There is also a bolt that is holding on a hold for this route.
content.location: Left of waterfall/damn, or left of flakes of wrath.

content.description: This is a fun climb.  The crux may be the bulge at the third to fourth bolt.  Good holds all the way to the anchors.
content.protection: Seven bolts; shuts
content.location: Start on the slick rock just left of the "dam"

content.description:
Sit start. Reach right up for the jug... if you can. No hug = no send. 

  This problem was established in appreciation of the incredible outpouring of support received when our dear friend suffered a serious injury while climbing.
content.protection: Pad, helmet!
content.location: South side of the boulder below Phantom / Fluid Dynamics. See pictures.

content.description: Bolted start to Public Hanging. Starts 4' to the right of the crack.
content.protection: Climb past 3 standard hangers to access the white weld shuts that comprise the rest of Public Hanging.

content.description: A fun route that starts in a corner crack (hence the need for 15' of crack pro) or as a variation could be started on the stem/face to the right (Capital Punishment) which would be in keeping it a pure sport route. Nice climbing thru the initial bolts becoming increasingly more challenging as one nears a bulge in a quasi-stemming dihedral (the crux), thence easier climbing (less challenging then it first appears) to the belay anchors.
content.protection: 8 bolts and a couple of cams medium to large, or if the variation is done- 10 bolts (including a  sling for the 2nd bolt).
content.location: Upon first entering the creek/canyon, it's the 2nd bolted route on the North side. Be aware, the bolts start some 35' above the creek.

climbs.name: Phantom
climbs.fa: Jim Steagall,  Eric Hanson, Dave Sobocan

content.description: An airy and fun route which features bolted laybacking to start (12a). The whitish overhanging face above (the 2nd crux) can be done by side-clipping the bolt from the left and doing a major "hook around" left as well (this would be the easiest way). We elected to stay but a foot or two left of the bolt and thought it to be 12b.   Toproping the bolt straddling version later felt a good deal harder.
content.protection: 7 bolts.
content.location: The 6th route met in the canyon on the North side of the creek.

content.description:
A classic.  A bit exciting getting established on the face above the last bolt; fun stuff!  A must do climb. 

  Start on slick, water polished rock located at an apex of the pool area below the dam; look for a short dihedral near the top of the wall.
content.protection: bolted
content.location: Left side of a buttress adjacent (left) to the schizophrenic buttress (photo provide for schozo.).

content.description: Climb the slick face just right of Neptune.  You can clip the first bolt of Neptune, but it will likely give you a bit of drag towards the top.  The climbing is easy to the first bolt proper anyways.  Pull through a few bulges on pockets, crimps, and a few jugs.
content.protection: 7-8 bolts plus 2 bolt cold shut anchor on the ledge.  All safe falls, but cruxy moves a bit above the 3rd or 4th bolt, with potential for a nice fun whipper.
content.location: Start 10' right of Netpune.

content.description: Start up the apron just right of Phantom. Clip a couple bolts then find your way up the white overhanging scoop. Continue up the crimpy and pocketed headwall.
content.protection:
Bolts 

  -Loose rock potential-
content.location: Right of Phantom, left of All Kings Men

content.description: Getting over the rooof is the crux, This climb is a must do for an 11 climber, fun with big moves on big holds.  Short and can be pumpy
content.protection: 4 bolts, 2 bolt anchor, make sure you have someone follow and clean otherwise its very hard to get your draws from under the roof.
content.location: Above the waterfall and damn thing.  Just right of smokin guns and left of shark attack.  This area is in the back by the wall.

content.description: Start on top of the dam and make your way left and up to the first bolt on the slab (stick clip recommended). Clip another bolt and the short crux begins. Figure out the strong, tricky sequence and find a hidden jug just above the fourth bolt. Pull over the overhang following the crack to the anchors.
content.protection: 5 bolts to anchors
content.location: Start on dam, left of Flakes of Wrath

climbs.name: Feast and Famine
climbs.fa: Ken Mills, Jimmy Steagall & Eric Hanson '92'

content.description:
This climb has two cruxes; pulling the first overhang/ roof and then pulling the second roof. 

  Awesome climbing on fairly steep rock.  Either do the boulder problem start, or by-pass on the right;  scramble up the slab to the first overhang/ roof for the first bolt.
content.protection: 7 bolts to a two shut rap.
content.location: The fourth climb on your left as you enter the corridor proper (as I recall- I will look this up)- look for a bulgy overhang ~ one meter off the deck, followed by a slab run to a second overhang/ roof.  A second small roof (~60 feet) can be seen from the deck.

content.description: After a hands roof crack pulling the lip is the Crux. Worth all you got!!
content.protection: sm to md pro
content.location: Starts in a crack just left of Smoking Guns. Head out roof crack. There is a cool knee bar against your right hand, that locks you in to free your left hand. Watch for your rope to get pinched in the crack as you climb above the roof. It merges into Smoking Guns and shares the anchors. On the FA I pulled a basket ball size boulder off just after the roof, managed to chuck it past my belayer, and still snag the Red Point. What a climb!!!

content.description: A route that features non-challenging moves for the most part- except the crux. It shares the start with Armed and Dangerous so consequently a stick-clip should be considered. The crux has some very bouldery moves far harder then it's origional rating of 12a (felt 12c), not made any easier by a critical pocket whose floor is gone making the hangerless bolt that protects it a moot point (we placed a temporary add-a-bolt sling to protect this section).
content.protection: 7 bolts (tho the crux bolt is hangerless)
content.location: The 3rd route one encounters on the North side of the creek.

climbs.name: Brush Your Teeth Before You Kiss Me

content.description: Start under a small roof and follow crack to the first bolt, then traverse right onto face to the next bolt on thin face, once past the first bolt get over the face and on to big ledge, the next bolt is up and left, climb up to the bolt with good holds, then traverse left to bulge with crack, it is probly a good idea to place a .4 alien here, because if you fall it is going to be an implesent whipper.  Here is some beta, there is a huge, bomber hold over the bulge in the back, once you get that stand on the ledge and clip next bolt, Then climb face past 2 more bolts to chain rappel.
content.protection: 5 bolts, chains, .4 alien(optional)
content.location: When coming into the Atlantis area it will be the first route on your left, look for big bulge with small crack.

content.description: Fun route with nice positioning. Shares the same start with Capital Punishment (hence a physical, slick chimney/face up to the initial bolt- best stick-clipped). Climbs overhanging easy face while side clipping bolts from the right. Crux is on bolt 5 and consists of a traverse to the left (and a shake-out jug) and then powering thru a crack (with a pinch hold) that allows bumps to hueco buckets for the left hand.
content.protection: 7 bolts
content.location: Starts 15' right of Public Hanging (the 4th bolted route encountered in the canyon North side) just left of a corner.

content.description: Make sure that you get a good clip for the third bolt or else the whipper is no fun at all.  The crux is obvious just by looking at the route.  Honestly i think this is one of the coolest routes here at Atlantis.  Also make sure that you place longer draws above the roof because of the sharp edge.
content.protection: Bolts, bolted anchors.
content.location: Left of trinity is my name.  Its the same start for 2 other routes to the left.  Basically the easiest route to find, the obvious huge flat roof.

content.description:
The north side routes are on the left side of the canyon when first entering after coming down the approach trail. 

  The north side routes tend to be steeper and more difficult than the south side. Many good, steep 5.10 and up exist here.  Mostly good rock on the routes, but don't forget it is still Queen Creek and the occasional bit of loose stuff is standard. 

This is the wall you rappel down if you choose to enter the area that way. You'll rappel right over  Neptune , which is a very popular 5.10. Please be careful tossing ropes if the parking lot already has cars in it and climbers are likely down there. Consider walking down instead as a courtesy to anyone unseen, who may be leading it below.
